===Etymology===
{{PIE root|en|gʷelH}}
Perhaps from {{inh|en|enm|qualm}}, {{m|enm|cwalm||death, sickness, plague}}, which is from {{inh|en|ang|cwealm}} {{gloss|West Saxon: "death, disaster, plague"}}, {{m|ang|ūtcualm}} {{gloss|Anglian: "utter destruction"}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*kwalm||killing, death, destruction}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*gʷelH-||to stick, pierce; pain, injury, death}}, whence also {{m|en|quell}}.  Although the sense development is possible, this has the problem that there are no attestations in intermediate senses before the appearance of "pang of apprehension, etc." in the 16th century. The alternative etymology is from {{bor|en|nl|kwalm}} or {{bor|en|de|Qualm}} "steam, vapor, mist," earlier "daze, stupefaction", which is from the root of {{der|en|de|quellen|t=to stream, well up}}. The sense "feeling of faintness" is from 1530; "uneasiness, doubt" from 1553; "scruple of conscience" from 1649.

